      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension is the primary driver, which is the heavy, grinding force you put on the muscle fibers, like when you lift a heavy load. Metabolic stress, on the other hand, is the \"pump\" feeling caused by the buildup of metabolites like lactate during high-rep, short-rest sets. Both are important, but maximizing mechanical tension is generally considered the most potent stimulus for hypertrophy. Think of it this way: tension is the *force* applied, and metabolic stress is the *byproduct* of the intense work.",
      "source": "target",
